{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_diamond_ver01/data/sn87065469/00383344013/1921011301/0038.xml":{"full_text":"a EAGLE\n-GEORGE W. PRICE. Editor and Publish^ _ WHICH WE FIGHT. Subscription. $2.00 per Year, In Advance. Single Copy. 5c.\nVol. 45. Oxford, Lafayette County, Miss., Thursday, January 13, 1921 No. 10\nSays Great Navy\nOnly Alternative\nFor Disarmament\nDaniels Tells Congressmen Proposal\nto Make IJ. S. Sea Power Less Than\nStrongest is Unworthy.\nWashington, Jan. 11 \u2014An in\nternational agreement with all, \u201cor\npractically all, the nations which will\nguarantee an entl of competition in\nnavy-building,\u201d was presented as the\nonly alternative to the building by\nthe United States of a navy power\nful enough \u201cto command the respects\nand fear of the world,\u201d by Secretary\nDaniels in testimony today before\nthe 'house naval affairs committee.\nThe naval secretary, who appeared\nbefore the committee in connection\nwith' its consideration of the subject\nof disarmament, dismissed as un\nworthy of discussion- a third pro\nposal for an American navy less\nthan equal to the most powerful sea\npower in the world \u201cbecause it is a\nwaste of money to spend money on\nan agency of war which would be\nhelpless if needed.\u201d\n\u201cin presenting his view's to the\ncommittee, Mr. Daniels took occasion\nto outline the advice which he would\ngive to President-elect Harding\nshould be asked for counce] on\nnaval matters. This advice took the\nform of a suggestion that Mr. Hard\nmg, immediately upon ins n^uguiu\ntion, Invite the nations of the world\nto meet with representatives of the\nUnited States in a disarmament con\nference. Authority for such action\nwas given by the naval appropria\ntion act of 191G, the secretary said,\nadding that if President Wilson\n\u2018should call a conference it would be\nimpossible for him to make recom\nmendations before his term of office\nexpires.\u201d\n\u201cLeague of Disarmament.\n\u201cIf President-elect Harding should\ndo me the honor to ask my advice\non the subject,\u201d declared Mr. Dan\niels, \u201cI would unhesitatingly say to\nhim:\n\u2018If the United States is not to be\ncome at once a member of the league\nof nations I believe some plan should\nbe adopted at once to secure an\nagreement for a induction of arma\nments. You will have the authority\nto call such a conference. You can\nact on March 5 and. hasten the com\ning of the day when taxpayers of\nthis country and of all counti'ies may\nbe safely freed from the great bur\ndens of the war preparations. Until\nthat conference secures world agree\nment let there be no cessation in\nbuilding the ships authorized by Con-1\ngres.\u201d\nCharacterizing the \u201cnaval holiday\u201d\nbetween the United States, Great\nBritain and Japan provided for in the\npending resolutions inti'oduced by\nSenator Borah, of Idaho, as \u201ca half\nway measure,\u201d Mr. Daniels reiterated\nhis opposition to this country enter\ning into such an agreement.\n\u201cA naval holiday for one year or\nany period is like applying a poul\ntice when surgery is needed,\u201d de\nclared the secretary. \u201cIt is little if\nany better than the sugested half\nway agreement between the United\nStates and two nations which have\na treaty of alliance. An alliance lim\nited to' the United States, Great\nBritain and Japan would make for\nsuspicion and distrust and would be\nToiioweu later uy <x iuu.iwi cmcuc m\nnations jealous of what they regard\nas an Anglo-Saxon and Japanese alli\nance to dictate to the world.\nHOLIDAYS MERELY REST.\n\u201cHolidays indicate a cessation from\nwork for a brief period with a view\nto returning to the old job when the\nholiday is over,\u201d Mr. Daniels aded.\n\u201cThe only wise course is to end\ncompetitive navy building, hot for one\nyear or five years and not for a few\nnations, but for all time by all nations.\nThe time is ripe for securing such an\nagreement now and I would consider\nit a serious mistake to fail to embrace\nthe opportunity for a permanent pol\nicy of reduction by accepting in its\nplace a substitute in the form of a\nterminable and unsatisfactory holi\nday. The world is asking for no play\ntime but for serious business.\u201d\nSecretary Daniels told the com\nmittee that in his annual report of\n1913^ and in each succeeding report\nhe had proposed an international con\nference to end competitive naval con\nstruction.\n\u201cI stand today where I stood in\n1913, when I was called a \u2018little navy\nman,\u2019 declared the secretary, \u201cfor\ninternational action or a navy second\nto none in the world. This, country\nwould demean itself by advocating^q.\nnavy second to any riation on. earth.\u201d\nActing Secretary Davis, of the state\ndepartment, told the committee, when\nasked his views regarding the siqeer\nity of the nations in their efforts to\nbring about reduction of armaments,\nthat he could say only that the powers\nwhich had subscribed to the covenant\nof the league of nations had mani\nfestly indicated their sincere desire to\nreduce armaments.\nTO THE WOMEN VOTERS OF\nOXFORD.\nA new day has dawned for the\nwomen. We have been given the right\nof franchise, and with the right, also\nhas come the moral obligation and\nduty to vote.\nThe world at large has beep looking\nto the women to cleanse politics. Much\nhot air has been expeded on this sub\nject, and needless bouquets thrown at\nour heads in an effort to touch our\nvanity. But the truth remains, that\nif the women don\u2019t land a helping\nhand we are worse off than before.\nWe, as Hue women of Oxford, are to\nhave our first chance to help in this\ncleansing, on Jan. 21, and let us be\nawake to this, our new duty, and go\nabout it in the right spirit, and stand\nclear an above petty politics when we\neast our vote. As women, we must\nlive up to what has'been claimed for,\nan expected of us, and thiow our in\nfluence for the right irrespective of\nfactions within the party lines.\nFirst of all let us inquire intp the\nmoral life of each candidate, and if it\nwill not stand close inspection, then\nfor the safety of our homes, as well as\nthe public good, see to it that our\ni-. mil. ,|>V| n rd-nmll>\nV/ tv l\u2019 >.11 V. VUOW L VI U I \u00bbin I vu\nclean and honest before the world.\n\u201cIf a man be riot square in his own\nlife\nThen it must follow as night the day.\nHe cannot be square with any man,\n(or the town either.)\nA WOMAN VOTER.\nAt the big cotton convention held\nin Memphis, December 8th and 9th,\nwhich was largely attended by farm\ners, bankers and merchants from the\nCotton Belt, it was agreed that the\nonly way to stabilize the price of the\ngreat staple of the South was to re\nduce the acreage of 1921 so that we\nwould raise a crop 50 per cent less\nthan that of 1920.\nIt was decided, after a careful sur\nvey of the situation that the most\nreasonable and effective plan was to\nformulate a rule that could be univer\nsally applied, which is as follows:\nHAVE EVERY FARMER IN THE\nSOUTH TO AGREE TO PLANT NOT\nMORE THAN ONE THIRD OF HIS\nLAND UNDER CULTIVATION\nto cotton in 1921.\nThis plan will result in a great di\nversification on the part of the farm\ner and will, if followed up from year\nto year, in the opinion of such an ex\npert as Bradford Knap, put the south\non a more solid financial basis than it\nhas ever been before.\nIn oreder to carry out the work of\nputting this plan into effect, the State\nBankers\u2019 Associations, together with\nthe State Divisions ot the American\nCotton Assocation, the Merchants As\nsociations and the Farmers\u2019 Unions\nand other farm organizations are co\noperating in the organization of the\nState.\nIt was the concensus of opinion of\nthe Memphis convention that the en\nforcement of this plan would not only\ncause an advance in the price of cot\nton now on'hand, but would also in\nsure a higher price for the 1921 yield.\nWHY RAISE FOURTEEN MIL\nLION BALES, IF WE CAN GET\nJUST AS MUCH OR MORE FOR\nSEVEN MILLION Bales and at the\nsame time raist plenty of food stuffs.\nIf this policy of sane farmng had\nbeen in force for the past ten years,\nthe South would now be rich.\nAhd still, our gunmen of today\n1 serve one good purpose. They are so\nnumerous \u00abno foreign country would\nhave the temerity to tackle us.\n\nFriends are like dollars\u2014when you\nneed them most they are hardest to\nfind. ,.v,\nForeigners come to this country\nI with the popular idea that America\nis a land flowing with milk end honey.\nIt is, but they soon learn that it re\nquires something besides m. and h. Jo.\nfill an empty stomach.\nLives of Many Poisoned Victims\nSaved By the Stomach Pump\nI IS just a piece ui rubber tuoing\nsix reei long anu auout ns big\narum as tue oruinary tuoing useu\nto con gas stoves, wild a snian\nuuib ii. e miaule ana a funnel,\nabout ti rt incnes in diameter, at one\nena.\nlet, according to the records of the\nLouisville City Hospital, it has saved\nfifty-eight lives since the first of this\nyear and many times that number\nin previous years.\nTechnically it is known as a stom\nach pump.\u201d But only to physicians,\nnurses and others wno are familiar\nwith the instrument and use it in\ntheir daily life do those two words\nmena a piece of rubber tubing. In\nquiry among laymen developed the\nfact that most persons think of a\nstomach pump as something like a\nbicycle pump, with a tube which is\nthrust down the victim\u2019s throat while\ntne operator with steady strokes slow\nly pump out me contents or tne stom\nacii. xn reality an tne pumping taut\nis uone is tne squeezing ana releas\ning or tne .bum, a simple opeiatmn oy\nwhich a small cnnu couia start me\ncontents or a nusxy man s stomacu to\nnow mg outwaru in a steady stream.\nbut the hard part of the operation\ndoes not consist in the actual pumping.\n.No child or no man is able to get tne\neighteen inches on the \"business end'\nof the pump down the tnroat of the\naverage person wno submits to the\noperation oi pumping.\nPhysicians at the hospital say that\nit is usually tne sign ior a great\nbattle when a victim of wood aiconoi\nor other poison is brought in. The\nprocess of getting that eighteen in\nches of tubing down tne human throat\nis very painful to the \u2018\u2018pumpee,\" wno\nin rtiost cases resists with all the\nstrength he or she can muster for tne\noccasion, J\\s many doctors and or\nderlies as are available assist in hold\ning tne patient while tne tube goes\ndown.\nit isn\u2019t long alter that until tne\nperson being pumped becomes quiet\nand meek. When the end of the tube\nhas reached the stomach about a\nquart of warm water is poured into\ntne funnel. Then the bulb is squeezed\nand released and the real pumping be\ngins. W hen the contents of tne stom\nach have been removed a small\namount of a solution of magnesium\nsulphate is jioured in and pumped out.\nThen a larger amount of the same so\nlution is poured in and allowed to re\nmain. By that time the patient is\nready to lie quitely on his bed and\nnot worry about the rest of the world.\nOf the fifty-eight emergency cases\nin which the stomach pump has been\nused at the local hospital since Jan\nuary, 1, forty were cases of poisoning\ndue to wood alcohol, Jamaica ginger\nand other whisky substitutes, while\neighteen were cases where other poi\nsons had been taken, either accidental\nly or with suciclde intent. There has\nbeen only one person who died from\n\u201cdrinking something\u201d at the City Hos\npital this year. He was an aged man\nREADY FOR \u201cACTION.\u201d\nI Dr. a. li. Woodward, member of the\nresident stall or tne Louisville City\nHospital vvitn tire ever-ready stomacn\npump. Dr. Woodward is one of the\n'niost eflieont pumpers at the hospital\n1 emu is aiways sougni in an emergency\ni to help prepare the \u201cvictim\u201d for tne\n1 operation. __\nfrom the country, Yvho drank a con\ncetrated solution of spirits of am\nmonia for stomach troubles, thinking\nit Yvas diluted. His death was caused\nby burns to the throat.\nThe stomach pump is always\nbrought into use when poison is sus\npected. Certain poisons, such as car\nbolic acid, take effect on the mem\nbranes immediately, and the pump is\nof little use, but in many cases where\na large amount of poison like bi\nchloride of mercury is taken, wash\ning out the stomach removes a part\nof the poison and saves life. In cases\nof arsenic, lead poisoning anj the like\nthe pump never fails if applied in\ntime.\ni Whether the people of Louisville\nget hold of better whisky substitutes\nand take\\veaker poisons than persons\nin other cities or Ythether the staff at\nthe City Hospital here is the most\nefficient in the country, might be a\nmooted question, but the fact remains\nthat while victims of poison and alco\nhol are dying in other places, here\nthey get their stomachs pumped and\nare ready for work the next morning.\n1 \u2014Louisville, (Kyi) Times, Oct. 15, \u201920.\nl\ni 6krk *Ko\\es awd Commew\\s\nI .firs. A. F. L'alotway. _ I\n\u201cThose that be planted in the house\nof the Lord shall flourish in the courts\nof our God.\u201d Psa. 92:13.\nTen teachers from the Methodist\nChurch School took a Training course\nunder Rev. R. H. Gladney, of Sar\ndis, field Secretary. This is a for\nward movement and no doubt will tell\nfor good in this respective school.\nMiss Mary E. Doney, and her splen\ndid class of Junior boys, entertained\nthe Junior girls class with a focial\nFriday evening, in the Sunday School\nroom.\nRev. W. I. Hargis was called to Ab\nbeville a few days ago, to conduct the\nfuneral, of a little grandson of Mr.\nJ. Anderson. The child died of Dip\ntheria.\nRev. W. L. Smith preached at\nWater Valley last .Sunday, .and will\npreach at the Primitive Church here,\nnext Sunday the 16th.\nOur young brother, G. W. Robert\nson, is doing a good work With his\nchurches, in spite of his University\nwork. He is filling his appointments\nregularly, and is giving his people\nhelpful gospel. He preached at Mid\nway last Sunday.\nBrother H. C. Smith, another young\npreacher of out towrlj has been called\nto serve New Prospect and Yellow\nLeaf, and is giving full proof of his\nministry. God bless these young\n\u201cSoldiers of the Cross,\u201d and make\nthem an increasing blessing. They\nhave chosen that good part which\nshall not be taken away from them.\nA season* of prayer for the success\nof all activities of the church, is being\nobserved at the Baptist church each\nafternoon of this and next week.\nThis example is worthy of emulation\nby the best.\nCHURCH NOTES.\nRev. Joseph Rennie, of Greenwood,\nis. holding a series of prepatory com\nmunion services, Wednesday, Thurs\nday, and Friday, at the Presbyterian\nChurch.\nThe University Circle of the Pres\nbyterian Church, met with Mrs. W. D.\nHedleston, Monday afternoon. They\nare studying the book of Ephesiem.\nThe Women\u2019s Missionary Society\nof the Methodist Church, met at Mrs.\nB. S. Guyton\u2019s home Monday after\nnoon. A 'very interesting business\nmeeting was held, and the* newly\nelected officers took their places.\nThe Misses Kirkwood entertained\nthe young ladies Sunday School Class\nof the Presbyterian Church at their\nhome, Tuesday evening.\n_'_*\nLIGHT SNOW AT MEMPHIS\nMemphis, Tenn., Jan; 13\u2014Mem\nphians awoke this, (Thurday morn\ning,) to find a 5-inch blanket of snow\nthat was followed by sleet and a driz\nzling rain. It was the first' rHii fall\nof the year, although flakes drifted\ndown early on the morning of Jan.9,\ndisappearing before the *Workeig\nreached the streets.\nA bad wound, burn or cut should be\ncleansed of dirt, or impurities and\ndressed with Liquid Borozohe. It heals\nthe flesh with marvelofls speed. Price,\n30c, 60c, and $1.20. Sold by A. H.\nKendel. .M-. Adv.\nOur city friends take a peculiar de\nlight at cracking jokes at the expense\n[of country people, but when they want\nto spend a week or two in complete\n.safety from banditry they invariably i\nhike for the tall grass.\nnm\nINJUNCTION BARS\nINSURANCE FIRMS\nABONDONING STATE\nMississippi Temporary Writ\nMade Permanent in Chancery\nCourt Opinion in Billon Dol\nlar Suit.\nJackson, Miss., Jan. 12.\u2014A\ntemporary injunction granted\nten days ago on petition of State\nRevenue Agent Stokes V. Rob\nertson, to prevent 160 fire in\nsurance companies from with\ndrawing from the State of Mis\nsissippi was today made per man\nnent by Chancellor V. J. Strieker j\nin Hinds county chancery court- j\nrlhe chancellor overruled the\ncontention of the insurance com\npanies that the revenue agent is j\nwithout authority to.resort to in\njunction and that his powers are\npurely statutory.\nThe fact that the revenue\nagent has the power to sue in\ni 1 _ f aI-aIa nmro\ntilt: uaiiu: ux uic\nChancellor Strieker, entitles him\nto use an injunction ancillary; a\nwrit of garnishment, subpoena,\nduces tecum or other necessaTy\nprocesses and he con not be re\ngarded as a litigant below the\nlevel of the common man*\nIn a lengthy written opinion,\nthe chancellor holds that if the\ninsurance companies should;\nwithdraw from the state \u201cas .the\nresult of a conspiracy, then such\naction would be an end of the\nsubject matter within the state,\nand a public calamity precipita-;\nted by a crime of the most rep\nrehensible character.\u201d\nJ The empanies opposing the in\njunction are defendants in the\nbillion-dollar antitrust suit filed\nby the state revenue agent an\nswer to which is now pendng.\nPROSPERITY AHEAD.\nThere is much comfort to be had\nfrom the statement recently of Judge\nElbert H. Gary, head of the United\nStates Steel corporation, the greatest\nbusiness concern the world ever pro\nduced.\n_ 1__sy-C I\njudge vjrary\nwonderful prosperity is just ahead of\nthe people of the United States.\nWhen Judge Gary opens his mouth\nhe is in the habit of saying something,\nand he never says a thing unless he\nknows what he is talking about.\nhas been a wise prophet in the\npast, because he possesses the ability\nto read conditions and possibilties as\nthey are.\nThere is no reason why his prophe\nsy should not be one of wisdom in\nthis case, because .there is no reason\nwhy we should.not prosper and every\nreason why we should.\nBanks and financiers generally\nstate that we have passed through our\nworst.period of depression and are\nnow on the up grade. Only the rank\nest kind of pessimism can hold us\nback.\nf. And who wants to be a pessimist\nwhen evejr human- instipct spurs us on\nto optisism\nLet\u2019s demonstrate our faith in the\nreturn of prosperity by recognizing\nthe fact that it is, here and by doing\nout share toward its maintainance in\nthis community. 1\nLet the watchword, be production,\nwisdom in spending, and the employ\nment of a systematic course of saving.\nA proportionate amount of the pros\nperity of the-country belong to the\npeople of this community.\nLet\u2019s get all we Can and keep all we\nget.\ni- Other communities will be doing the\nsame.\n-j-\u2014\nY\nTom Watson To Propose Radical\nStep In Senate.\n\nSenator-elect Thomas E. Watson,\nof Georgia, announces in a copyright\ned statement published in the Atlan\nta Constitution, that at the extra ses\nsion of the 7th Congress he will in\ntroduce a bill to make Liberty and\nVictory bonds and other government\nwar paper legal tender.\nUr. Watson also announced plans\nfor introducing bills to force the fed\neral reserve and farm loan banks to\n.end money directly to individuals\nanti to require the secretary of the\ntreasury to issue the unissued green\nbacks authorized by a bill signed by\nPresident Lincoln. The total of these\nauthorized but unissued greenbacks,\naccording to the senator-elect, is\n$102,000,000.\nDiscussing his plan to make legal\ntender of Liberty and Victory bonds,\ncredit certificates, war savings stamps\nand all government obligation paper\nissued during and since' the world war\nas a remedy for what he claims is an\nexisting \u201cdomestic crisis,\u201d Mr. Wat\nson declared such action would have\nan electrifying7, effect upon American\nbusiness life.\nSuch action, he said, \u201cwill not in\ncrease the government\u2019s obligation\none dollar, bufc-will immediately bring\nfrom the bank vaults, private safes,\nbureau drawers, tin boxes and stock\nings billions of dollars of. circulating\nlegal tender, now inactive and salable\nonly at a loss, and enable the people\nto pay their debts to each other, the\nconsumer to the merchant, the mer\nchant to the small banker, the small\nbanker to his corerspondent, and so\non.\u201d\nOn pasage of such legislation, Mr.\nWatson declared, \u201call apprehension\nof a panic would quickly disappear.\nRegarding the nation\u2019s financial\"\nsystem, Mr. Watson said he would in\ntroduce bills to make it mandatory\nunder penalty for the regional banks\nto lend direct to farmers on appoved\nsecurities at an interest rate not over\n5 per cent; to repeal that section of\nthe farm loan bank act \u201cRequiring a\ngroup of 10 sognatories to a loan and\ninsertion of a mandatory clause com\npeling such banks to lend to an in\ndividual applicant upon approved se\ncurity without the requirement of ad\nditional obligators.\nopposition to an increase in. taxes\nor to a higher tariff and a desire for\nre-establishment of pre-war trade ge\nlations with Russia and Germany\nwere expressed by Mr. Watson in the\nsame statement. He also favored\nending the war \\yith Germany by\nresolution.\nNOTICE TO ALL CREDITORS OF\nTHE MERCHANTS AND\nFARMERS BANK.\nNotice is\" hereby given that on the\n10th day of January, A. D. 1921, an\norder was made and entered in the\ncause entitled R. C, Carter, et al. Vs.\nDuke M. Kimbrough, et al. No. 4775,\nin the Chancery court of Lafayette\ncounty* Mississippi, thereby the Un\ndersigned was appointed a special re\nceiver and master in said cause, and\nordered to give notice to all creditors\nof the Merchants and Farmers Bank,\nof Oxford, Lafayette county, Missis\nsippi, that on the 24th day of January,\nA. D. 1921, at. 10 A. M. in the office\nof the chancery clerk of said county\nand state, all the creditors of the said\nMerchants and Farmers Bank may\npresent or asert any right dr. elpim to\nany part of the fund directed to be.\npaid by said order by the defendants*\nin said cause;\nNow, therefore, you are hereby no\ntified that op said date, to\u2019wit, the\n24th day of January, A. D. 1921, you\nmay, at the place aforesaid, present\nyour claim to me, duly sworn to,\nshowing the amount you claim to be\ndue you by tfie said Merchants and\nFarmers Bank.\nWitness my signature, this the 13,\nday of January, A. D. 1921.\nW. M. WOODWARD,\nSpecial Receiver and Master.","height":"33104","width":"22460"}}
